<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Beats North 98-84 to Win CBA All-Stars Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 5 (Xinhua) -- This season's MVP Hu Weidong
poured in a game-high 42 points to lead the South team for a 98-84
victory over the North side at the third All-Stars Game of the
Chinese Basketball Association's first division league here on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Hu also captured the game's MVP for his brilliant performance.
</P>
<P>
He hit 19 points in the first nine minutes of the game and
lifted the South side to a 31-15 early lead.
</P>
<P>
But sparked by 20 points from James Hodges, a American pro
hired by the Liaoning Hunters, the North stars rallied strongly
when Hu sit out in the rest of the first half. The two teams tied
the score 42-42 in the first half.
</P>
<P>
The two sides exchanged lead seven times till Hu's lay-up put
the South team to a 66-65 lead at the 10th minute in the second
half.
</P>
<P>
The South stars used a 10-1 run, including two straight
3-pointers from Hu, to build up a 76-66 lead with seven minutes to
go.
</P>
<P>
Hu hit two more 3-pointers while Liu Yudong of the Bayi Rockets
hit 9 of his 17 points to help South stars to a 98-84 victory.
</P>
<P>
The star players also entertained the 17,000-strong crowd with
three-point shooting and slam-dunking competitions during the
break.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai Oriental's Saulius Stombergas of Lithuania captured
the long-range shooting trophy with 17 successful shots, ousting
Li Xiaoyong and Wu Qinglong of the Liaoning Hunters. Li and Wu
finished with 16 and 15 respectively.
</P>
<P>
Hodges grabbed the slamdunking title with 360-degree spin dunk,
which brought him 46 points out of a perfect 50.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai's Liang Da jumped from some four meters in front of
the backboard and soared over about two meters in the air for a
dunk, but the Chinese player missed the target, scoring only 36
points for the runner-up. 
</P>
</TEXT>
