<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Grand National Horse Race Abandoned After Bomb Threats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 5 (Xinhua) - The Grand National horse race, one
of Britain's greatest sporting events, had to be abandoned today
after bombing threat were sent to police.
</P>
<P>
Police told officials at Aintree course, near the north-west
city of Liverpool, to evacuate the whole race course and clear the
site after receiving coded warnings of two bombs on the site,
according to local reports.
</P>
<P>
Around 60,000 spectators plus the 38 jockeys were moved off the
site half an hour before the start of the scheduled race early in
the afternoon. Officials later abandoned racing for the rest of
the day.
</P>
<P>
Security forces carried out a controlled explosion at the
course after finding several suspect packages.
</P>
<P>
Although It was not immediately clear who had delivered the
bomb warnings, Prime Minister John Major blamed the IRA again for
the incident, saying he was "appalled that the IRA seem to be
threatening hundreds of thousands of people and causing such
disruption."
</P>
<P>
"This is further demonstration of their contempt and disregard
for the lives and interest of ordinary people," he said.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, police found two bombs on road bridges after
receiving coded telephone warnings, and two major motorways had to
be closed for more than 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
Four years ago the Grand National ended in turmoil in different
circumstances after two false starts led to the race being
declared void.
</P>
<P>
The IRA has been trying for more than 25 years to end British
rule of Northern Ireland. It called off a 17-month long ceasefire
in February, 1996, and has since exploded several large bombs on
the British mainland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
