<HEADLINE> S. Korean Trade Group Ends Visit to DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 5 (Xinhua) -- A South Korean semi-governmental
trade official said today that South Korea and the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) had discussed the possibility of
opening a South Korean trade office in its northern neighbor.
</P>
<P>
Ending an eight-day visit to Pyongyang today, Hong Ji-sun of
the Korea Trade and Investment Promotion Agency (KOTRA) said he
held talks with DPRK officials on the business opportunities in
the export processing industry.
</P>
<P>
He hinted that the two sides had made progress in opening a
trade office in DPRK's Rajin-Sonbong Free Trade and Economic
Zone. But he declined to give further details.
</P>
<P>
Hong promised to give a press conference on April 7 on the
negotiations, Yonhap News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
KOTRA and DPRK's External Economic Cooperation Committee agreed
in principle in 1995 to open an office of KOTRA in the economic
zone. But tension soon flared up and the plan was not carried
out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
