<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Efforts Urged to Halt Infectious Diseases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 5 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Environmental
Program (UNEP) has called for effective management of the
environment to halt emerging infectious diseases.
</P>
<P>
A news release issued by UNEP reaching here today said that
old infectious diseases such as malaria and tuberculosis have
resurged and new diseases like HIV have been discovered during
the past five years.
</P>
<P>
The release pointed out that many emerging and resurgent
infectious diseases may have been attributed to "extreme weather
conditions".
</P>
<P>
Many effects of global climate change on human health would be
adverse unless strict measures are undertaken to reduce
greenhouse gas emissions to the reasonable levels, it added.
</P>
<P>
Human interference with the natural flow of freshwater systems
has accelerated the spread of some infectious diseases while dams
and irrigation canals often serve as breeding areas for
mosquitoes, the release stressed.
</P>
<P>
Water pollution can spark outbreaks of cholera and dysentery,
said the release which was issued in commemoration of "The World
Health Day" on April 7.
</P>
<P>
The world environment body of UNEP noted that "human health
and that of the environment are intimately interlinked."
</P>
<P>
"Effective management of the environment will help to halt and
eventually stop these diseases," it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
