<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Proposed Merger of Two Office Suppliers Rejected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 5 (Xinhua) -- The U.S.Federal Trade Commission
rejected on Friday the proposed 4 billion U.S. dollars merger of
two office supply giants, Staple Inc. and Office Depot Inc.
</P>
<P>
The action, which is reported to reflect the aggressiveness in
anti-trust enforcement by the F.T.C. came after Staple and Office
Depot had agreed to sell 63 stores to their only other competitors
in the office supply superstore market, Officemax Inc.
</P>
<P>
The commission voted 4 to 1 to seek a Federal court injunction
against the merger, which would have created an office superstore
chain with more than 1000 stores and 10 billion U.S. dollars in
annual sales.
</P>
<P>
The proposed deal was an undisguised and illegal attempt to
eliminate competition between the two chains and would inevitably
lead to higher prices for consumers, William J. Baer, director of
the F.T.C. anti-trust division, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
In the last two years, the F.T.C. required several supermarket
and department store chains that sought to merge to divest
themselves to maintain competition in their regions.
</P>
<P>
The commision's action was applauded by consumer advocates and
was described as new evidence that the Clinton Administration is
serious about enforcing antitrust laws. 
</P>
</TEXT>
