<HEADLINE> UK Water Companies Accused over Big Leaks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Water companies in Britain are
losing more than a quarter of supplies through leaks, with Thames
Water at the top of 38.6 percent leaks.
</P>
<P>
The news released by Ofwat, the water industry regulator, came
with Britain facing a drought crisis after the driest two-year
period in England and Wales since records began over 200 years ago
in the country.
</P>
<P>
The statistics from the Institute of Hydrology underline the
fact that large parts of Britain's most densely populated region
will have hosepipe bans within a few months.
</P>
<P>
The shock leak figures forced Ofwat to slap leak reduction
targets on water companies, to ensure they made better progress in
tackling their leakage rate.
</P>
<P>
Ofwat said water companies will face heavy financial penalties
if there is not a rapid improvement. Thames Water was named as the
worst offender, losing almost four gallons out of ten through
leaks--more than 200 million wasted gallons a day.
</P>
<P>
Welsh Water was almost as bad, and North West Water and
Northumbrian Water were also picked out for strong criticism.
</P>
<P>
The regulator said, Britain's 10 privatized companies had a far
worse record than the 18 other water suppliers in England and
Wales.
</P>
<P>
The companies, who have been warning of hosepipe bans and
drought orders, were reportedly themselves handed multi-million
pound conservation ultimatum.
</P>
<P>
Tory MP Elizabeth Peacock, vice-chairman of the all-party
Commons water group called the leaks "outrageous", saying "Any
company losing more than 20 percent needs to act."
</P>
<P>
"It is difficult for people to accept a hosepipe ban when so
much water is being wasted," she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
