<HEADLINE> Zairean Peace Talks Begin in South Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 5 (Xinhua) -- The first round of talks
between the Zairean government and the rebel forces kicked off in
Pretoria today with both sides committing themselves to seeking a
peaceful solution to the conflict in their country.
</P>
<P>
Zairean Foreign Minister Kamanda Wa Kamanda said at the
opening of the talks that the Zairean government would approach
the talks with an open mind, stressing "we are going to look for
peace."
</P>
<P>
Kamanda expressed appreciation for the South African government's
mediation efforts, saying that he would welcome help from South Africa
to create conditions conducive to the progress and development of
Zaire.
</P>
<P>
Bizima Karaha, leader of the delegation representing the
Zairean rebels, said his delegation will take the opportunity of
the negotiation to "find peaceful and lasting solutions" to the
Zairean crisis.
</P>
<P>
South African Deputy President Thabo Mbeki said the outcome of
the current talks would have an impact on the length and breadth
of the politics on the African continent.
</P>
<P>
South Africa is one of four countries chosen at a summit in
Nairobi last December to spearhead peace efforts in Zaire, which
has for months been plagued by violent clashes between the
government troops and the rebels led by Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
Mohamed Sahnoun, the U.N. Special Representative for the Great
Lakes Region, attended the talks and said the delegations from
the warring sides in Zaire were fully aware of their
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
Sahnoun pointed out there should be no illusions about the
odds of such meetings producing spectacular results, but those
involved would leave no stone unturned to prepare the ground for
durable peace.
</P>
<P>
According to Mbeki, the peace talks would continue later in
the day under the co-chairmanship of Sahnoun and South African
Deputy Foreign Minister Aziz Pahad. enditem

