<HEADLINE> S.Africa's Development Trust Accelerates Funding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 5 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's Transitional
National Development Trust (TNDT) announced here today it had
accelerated funding to non-governmental organizations (NGO) and
community-based organizations (CBO) since the beginning of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The TNDT, established as an interim development funder in 1995
by the government, said in a statement that it had undergone a
priorization process because of the large volume of requests
received from NGO's and CBO's throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
The TNDT's original financing of 125 million Rand (about 28
million U.S. Dollars) came from the government and the European
Union.
</P>
<P>
The trust had so far received request totaling 1.2 billion
Rand (about 270 million Dollars) from about 1400 NGOs and CBOs,
said the statement.
</P>
<P>
TNDT General Manager Paul Jackson said about 10 million
Dollars had to date been committed to 141 projects assessed by
the trust.
</P>
<P>
Jackson said nearly 60 percent of the funds had been allocated to
the education and training sector, small, medium and micro
enterprises, rural and urban development, and good governance and
democracy.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed that TNDT's priority was given to projects
which emphasised community participation and benefited rural
areas, women and children. enditem
