<HEADLINE> Ekeus-Aziz Talks Secured No Substantial Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Rolf Ekeus, chairman of the UN
Special Commission on Iraq (UNSCO) announced that his talks with
Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tareq Aziz resulted in no substantial
progress, accusing Iraq of continuing to obstruct the work of the
UN arms inspection teams.
</P>
<P>
This came at a press conference held by Ekeus in the Iraqi
capital today after three days of talks with Aziz on the file of
Iraq's mass-destruction weapons.
</P>
<P>
According to sources close to Ekeus, the talks focused on
Iraq's chemical weapons and long-range missiles as well as Iraq's
efforts including written statement to allay the UN fears about
these weapons.
</P>
<P>
The sources added that the UN inspection teams need to verify
any Iraqi written announcement, to have interviews with the Iraqi
scientists who participated in Iraq's former armament programs,
and the UNSCO would complete its mission in Iraq within six months
if with smooth Iraqi cooperation.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Iraqi diplomatic sources also said that
Aziz assured Ekeus that Iraq has destroyed all the
mass-destruction weapons its possessed in the wake of the Gulf war
of 1991.
</P>
<P>
Political circles in Baghdad think that Ekeus' talks with Aziz
on Iraq's chemical weapons were the first of their kind since the
UN arms inspection teams started their mission in Iraq in April,
1991, and that the issue of Iraq' biological weapons is still more
complicated.
</P>
<P>
Ekeus arrived in Baghdad last Thursday, accompanied by four UN
arms inspectors, for a routine visit to Iraq. He will be leaving
Baghdad later today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
