<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 5 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- A large consignment of Egypt-made medicines reached
the Iraqi capital of Baghdad today for an Egyptian Medicine Fair
to be held on April 8.
</P>
<P>
This will be Egypt's first medicine fair held in Iraq since the
United Nations partially removed economic sanctions against it
late last year, the Egyptian MENA news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Altogether 20 Egyptian firms specialized in the production and
manufacturing of drugs will participate in the exhibition
organized by the Egyptian Holding Company for medicines in
cooperation with the Iraqi Health Ministry, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The exhibited products will be later offered to the Iraqi
people to help relieve the medicine crisis caused by the six-year
international embargo imposed on the country, according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement signed between Iraq and Egypt in late
January, Egypt will export 3 million U.S. dollars of medicines to
Iraq. The first batch of the medicine has reportedly reached Iraq
in February.
</P>
<P>
Egypt expects the volume of exports to Iraq to reach 100
million U.S. dollars in the first six months of the implementation
of the U.N.-Iraqi oil-for-food deal starting from last December to
ease the impact of the trade sanctions imposed for Iraqi August
1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
In line with the deal, Iraq will be allowed to sell 2 billion
dollars of oil in six months to buy food and medicine.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt will dispatch a commercial promotion mission to
six southern African countries in a bid to boost the country's
exports.
</P>
<P>
The tour, starting in May, will include South Africa, Lesotho,
Swaziland, Botswana, Namibia and Mozambique, the Egyptian MENA
news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The mission will shed spotlight on a number of Egyptian
products including ceramics, carpets, leather products, shoes,
kitchen tools, aluminum, stainless steel, juices, jams, wood and
office furniture.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt will export to the United States 1 million
dozens of shirts worth nearly 50 million dollars, head of the
Egyptian Yarn Promotion Fund Mahmoud Ibrahim said today
</P>
<P>
The two countries have reached agreement recently on increasing
the quota by 10 percent annually as of next year, he said.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Egypt will also export certain types of
yarn, knitting fibers and cloth worth more than 50 million dollars
to the U.S. markets, he added.
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- Tourist arrivals in Cyprus dropped 14.5 percent in
February 1997 compared with the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
According to a report released today by the Cypriot Department
of Statistics and Research, the majority of travelers who
arrived in Cyprus last February came from European countries,
especially from the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the number of travelers passing through the
island's ports also reduced to 1,844 in February 1997 from 3,084
in February last year.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus attracts more than 2 million foreign tourists a year,
earning about 1.6 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
