<HEADLINE> Lebanon Pessimistic Over Clinton-Netanyahu Meeting, Minister Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Foreign Minister Farez
Boueiz said here today that he does "not expect much" from a
meeting to be held next week between Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu and U.S. President Bill Clinton in Washington.
</P>
<P>
He called on the U.S. to be "a just intermediary and a
pushing power in order to re-activate the peace process" in the
Middle East region.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese foreign minister underlined that the peace process
could not succeed but "by Israel's adherence to the principles
which was defined for this process since the beginning."
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-Israeli summit comes as the Middle East peace process
is threatened by high tensions between Israelis and the
Palestinians following the decision of Netanyahu's government to
build 6,500 homes for some 25,000 Jews at Jebel Abu Ghnaim, or
Har Homa, in Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Boueiz left here today for New Delhi, the capital of India, to
attend the conference of the non-aligned countries' foreign
ministers, which will be held on April 7.
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters at the Beirut International Airport before
leaving, the foreign minister said among the issues raised on the
agenda of the conference are the Arab-Israeli conflict, the
situation in south Lebanon and the Lebanese detainees in Israeli
prisons.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese official denied a report that Syria has decided to
withdraw from a five-nation committee supervising a limited truce
on the Lebanese-Israeli border, noting that Syria is "continuous
in its memberhood in the cease-fire monitoring committee."
</P>
<P>
Boueiz said that he held a telephone contact with his Syrian
counterpart Farouq al-Shara Friday on this issue.
</P>
<P>
The committee, comprising representatives of France, Israel,
Lebanon, Syria and the U.S., was established under a cease-fire
understanding reached between Lebanon and the Jewish state in
April 1996.
</P>
<P>
