<HEADLINE> Night Curfew Imposed on Somali District </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, April 5 (Xinhua)-- South Mogadishu faction leader
Hussein Mohamed Aidid today imposed a night curfew on Afgoe Distrct,
30 km south of here.
</P>
<P>
The curfew is effective tonight.
</P>
<P>
According to regulations, vehicles and pedestrians should stop
moving around from 24:00 local time to the sun rise in
the morning, otherwise they face the consequences.
</P>
<P>
All street vendors, cinemas, and restaurants are similarly
ordered to halt their activities after 24:00.
</P>
<P>
However, the movement of health personnel and patients is allowed
once they introduce their identities.
</P>
<P>
According to the Chief Security Officer of the district,
Hussein Ali Weheliye, all militiamen other than those on duty
should remain in their quarters and weapons seen circulating in
the town will be confiscated.
</P>
<P>
The imposition of the night curfew on the town was prompted
after the security situation there has been seriously threatened
by widespread freelance looting, kidnapping and rape against the
women especially at night.
</P>
<P>
The instability in Afgoe has increased since the interclan
clashes have began between clansmen in the region including Habar
Gidir, Garre, Murusadeh and Galadi.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time the administration of Hussein Aidid
imposes a night curfew on towns in southerm Somalia since June
1995. The town of Baidoa was the first place where the practice
had began after Rahanwein militiamen intermittently attacked the
bases of the militiamen of late faction leader Farah Aidid who
took over the control of the town in September 1995.
</P>
<P>
Also in November last year, a night curfew was imposed in
north Mogadishu after the collapse of the islamic courts
following Ali Mahdi's deeree sacking Sheikh Ali Dhere from the
chairmanship of the supreme islamic court. enditem

