<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Preserves Endangered Tree Species </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 5 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Agriculture
of Ethiopia said Friday the seeds of 53 different kinds of
endangered tree species are being distributed among tree-planters
in efforts to save them from extinction.
</P>
<P>
Solomon Retta, an expert from the ministry, said here that
almost 45,000 kilograms of local and foreign origin tree seeds
have been collected.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 35,000 kilograms of the seeds has been distributed
among 120 government and non-governmental organizations while the
remaining is stored in a convenient granary.
</P>
<P>
"We expected the organizations to germinate the seeds and
supply the seedlings to the people who need them," he said.
</P>
<P>
The trees could be used for fuel, construction, soil
conservation and in the making of medicinial drugs, he added.
</P>
<P>
Among the treey@re cardia africana, abyssinian juniper,
hygnea abysinica and podocarpus procera.
</P>
<P>
Imported trees such as eucalyptus, accacia, causuarina and
gravelea are also disappearing, he added.
</P>
<P>
Currently less than three percent of the country's landmass is
covered by forest. enditem

