<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Determine EMU Joiners in Late April or Early May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 5 (Xinhua) -- European Union finance ministers
agreed on Saturday at a meeting in the Netherlands that the
decision on which countries join the single currency, the Euro,
would be made in late April or early May.
</P>
<P>
Meeting informally together with EU central bankers in the
Dutch seaside town of Noordwijk, the ministers also endorsed plans
to penalize countries running excessive budget deficit -- above
three percent of GDP -- once they are part of the EMU, scheduled
to start on January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Countries wishing to join EMU must meet various criteria set
out in the Maastricht treaty on deficits, debt, inflation,interest
rates and exchange rates.
</P>
<P>
Though deluged in recent weeks by speculation about a delay in
the starting date for the Euro, the EU finance ministers
reaffirmed their commitment to the 1999 deadline.
</P>
<P>
The group also took stock of negotiations on a revamped
Exchange Rate Mechanism, dubbed ERM 2, and designed to link
countries outside EMU to the Euro.
</P>
<P>
Prior to March 1, 1998, each Member States is required to
provide the European Commission with final information on the
country's 1997 budget performance.
</P>
<P>
The Commission and the European Monetary Institute, the
forerunner of the future European Central Bank, will then have
roughly two weeks to come up with their convergence reports.
</P>
<P>
After the evaluation, there is a six-week consultation period
with the European Parliament, before a qualified majority decision
will be taken, at a meeting of Heads of state and Government of
the EU countries, to adopt the list of countries due to join the
Euro on January 1, 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
