<HEADLINE> Ordinance for Women's Property Rights Urged in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Women social workers in Nepal
today threatened to stage street demonstrations if the government
fails to enact a bill on women's equal property rights through
ordinances.
</P>
<P>
A group of women activists at a gathering here decided to call
a meeting of women representatives from all walks of life next
Wednesday and finalize their protest programs.
</P>
<P>
They also decided to meet Women and Social Welfare Minister
Sahana Pradhan, who was a strong proponent of the Women's property
rights bill before being appointed into the cabinet last month
when Prime Minister Lokendra Bahadur Chand formed his coalition
government.
</P>
<P>
The women rights workers said they would launch a relay hunger
strike and picket the prime minister's office and main ruling
parties' offices to protest the government's failure to legalize
women's inheritance rights for parental property.
</P>
<P>
Prior to that, a 15-day ultimatum for the implementation of the
government's commitment to social justice at international forums
and a memorandum to the prime minister on the demand will be
submitted, they said.
</P>
<P>
Social activists and women leaders here also urged the
government to introduce the bill on women's property rights
through ordinances after the parliament ended its winter session
last week without passing any important bills.
</P>
<P>
The parliament session had been expected to discuss and approve
some bills including the one on women's property rights.  
