<HEADLINE> Chubb Looking To Insure Cultural Property in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Executives of the US's Chubb
Corporation, one of the world's major insurers, are looking at
providing insurance for China's cultural property, a virgin land
for foreign insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
The company thinks its expertise can be used to provide a
protective canopy for China's rich cultural heritage, according to
Deano Hare, chairman of the board of Chubb.
</P>
<P>
Chubb is set to cooperate with the State Bureau of Cultural
Relics in an effort to teach the country's museum curators and
staff about cultural property insurance, and has sponsored a
program called "Friends of Chinese Treasures."
</P>
<P>
A local official estimates that China's insurance business may
be worth 250 billion yuan by the end of the century as more people
become aware of the importance of insurance in their lives, and
the country is gradually opening its insurance market to overseas
insurers.
</P>
<P>
Hoping to play a part in China's burgeoning insurance business,
especially in the field of culture, Chubb has set up offices and
centers in Beijng, Shanghai, and Shenzhen since 1992.
</P>
<P>
Hare said Chubb last year had assets of 20 billion US dollars.
</P>
