<HEADLINE> Grand National Horse Race Rescheduled for Monday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 6 (Xinhua) -- The Grand National horse race,
which was called off on Saturday after police received two bomb
warnings, will be run at 1600 GMT Monday, race officials announced
today.
</P>
<P>
Charles Barnett, managing director of Aintree racecourse, near
the northwest city of Liverpool, told a news conference that
trainers, owners and other interested parties have been notified,
and the vast majority have already indicated that their horses
will take part in the rescheduled running of the race.
</P>
<P>
"I am assured we can get the course right in time although
substantial damage has been done to the running rail and some of
the fences," he said.
</P>
<P>
Aintree chairman Lord Daresbury said: "The nation shared in
Saturday's disappointment but we all feel there is a huge
collective will for the Grand National to go ahead."
</P>
<P>
The 150th Grand National, one of Britain's greatest sporting
events, was abandoned and a crowd of around 70,000 spectators were
evacuated from the racecourse early Saturday afternoon. Security
forces carried out three controlled explosions on packages later
deemed to be harmless.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the BBC intends to offer live coverage of
the race. 
