<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> APEC Ministers Adopt Rules to Attract Private Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CEBU, The Philippines, April 6 (Xinhua) -- To ensure sustained
economic growth in the Asia Pacific, the finance ministers of the
Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) forum's 18 economies
today adopted a set of voluntary rules to facilitate sustained
capital flows into the region.
</P>
<P>
After their two-day meeting which ended here today, the finance
ministers adopted a joint ministerial statement, whose centerpiece
is the voluntary rules helping bring private capital into the
region.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, the finance ministers recognized
the importance of both private sector participation in
infrastructure development and sound financial and capital markets
in sustaining the growth momentum of the APEC region.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, they agreed to adopt these rules to stimulate
private sector investment in infrastructure and accelerate the
development of domestic financial and capital markets.
</P>
<P>
But according to the statement, all these rules will be
implemented on a voluntary basis with due respect for diversity
and different levels of economic development of each APEC member.
</P>
<P>
To encourage private investment in infrastructure, the
statement said, the APEC member economies agreed to pursue the
following rules:
</P>
<P>
-- Sound macroeconomic environment. Steady and sustained growth
based on sound macroeconomic fundamentals is the key to attracting
private sector investments in infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
-- Stable and transparent legal framework and regulatory
systems. A stable and transparent legal framework is a
prerequisite for attracting private investors and safeguarding
their interests.
</P>
<P>
-- Sectoral policies that promote competition. Where
applicable, member economies shall unbridle existing monopolies in
infrastructure to promote increased private sector participation,
competition, and consumer welfare.
</P>
<P>
-- Availability of long-term capital. Well-developed domestic
financial and capital markets play a crucial role in mobilizing
savings and making available longer-term capital for
infrastructure investments.
</P>
<P>
To promote financial and capital markets development, the
ministers also agreed that the following goals shall be achieved:
</P>
<P>
-- Sound macroeconomic environment. The pursuit of sound
macroeconomic policies is an essential element in maintaining
strong banking systems and a prerequisite to the development of
capital markets, including long-term debt markets.
</P>
<P>
-- Stable and transparent legal and regulatory systems. Sound
financial regulation and supervision is critical to capital
markets development.
</P>
<P>
-- Well-developed market infrastructure. High quality,
transparent and comparable reporting and disclosure on the
financial positions of business promote investor interests in
capital markets.
</P>
<P>
-- Financial and capital market instruments. Market-based
benchmark rates for medium to long term securities facilitate more
accurate pricing and encourage the development and deepening of
the bond market, including that for municipal bonds.
</P>
<P>
Besides the voluntary rules, the finance ministers also reached
agreement on collaborative initiatives in the two areas, proposed
by some leading APEC economies.
</P>
<P>
These initiatives include enhanced cooperation among export
financing institutions, strengthened financial market supervision,
well-developed clearing and settlement systems, and a voluntary
action plan for supporting the freer and stable flow of capital.
</P>
<P>
The implementation of these voluntary rules and collaborative
initiatives will be reviewed at the next APEC finance ministers'
meeting, due to be held next year in Canada. Canada currently
holds the rotating presidency of APEC.
</P>
<P>
APEC was established in 1989 in response to the growing
interdependence among the Asia-Pacific economies. It groups China,
the United States, Australia, Brunei, Canada, Chile, Hong Kong,
Indonesia, Japan, South Korea, Singapore, Chinese Taipei,
Thailand, New Zealand, Malaysia, Papua New Guinea, the Philippines
and Mexico.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970406.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Rules out Sinn Fein Entry Into Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 6 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister John Major
warned today that Saturday's bomb scare that wrecked the Grand
National horse race puts back Sinn Fein's entry into Northern
Island peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The 150th Grand National, one of Britain's greatest sporting
events, was cancelled Saturday after police received two coded
bomb warnings.
</P>
<P>
Major immediately laid blame on the Irish Republican Army (IRA)
for the alert although no one has claimed responsibility.
</P>
<P>
He told BBC TV's Breakfast With Frost program that he had no
doubt the bomb warnings were the work of the IRA.
</P>
<P>
If Sinn Fein, the political wing of the IRA, thought its action
would hasten an entry into peace talks, this was a "total and
utter misjudgment," Major said.
</P>
<P>
"It puts it back. It certainly doesn't put it forward," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The opposition Labor Party showed solidarity with Major, saying
that IRA tactics put Sinn Fein "beyond the pale" for talks after
the general election.
</P>
<P>
The minority Liberal Democratic Party leader Paddy Ashdown also
said Saturday's events would only serve to strengthen people's
anger.
</P>
<P>
Britain has refused to admit the Sinn Fein to the Northern
Island peace talks unless the IRA declares a lasting cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
The IRA, which has been fighting for more than 25 years to end
British rule in Northern Ireland, was believed by police to be
responsible for two other bomb alerts on British motorways last
Thursday. 
</P>
