<HEADLINE> Navigation Project Completed on China's Hanjiang River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, April 6 (Xinhua) -- The navigation-channel renovation
project on the Hanjiang River in central China's Hubei Province
has been completed, allowing 500-dwt ships to go downstream from
Xiangfan to Wuhan, the provincial capital.
</P>
<P>
The project cost a total of 243 million yuan, and allowed the
river to become another way to move coal from northern to southern
parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
The Hanjiang River is 1,567 km long and is the Yangtze's
largest tributary, originating in Ningqiang County in northwest
China's Shaanxi Province and entering the Yangtze in Hubei.
</P>
<P>
The Hanjiang, with its many bends and shallows, made navigation
very difficult before the renovation project, which included work
on a 532-km-long navigation course, construction of a coal port,
and a telecommunications system. The project began in 1990, and
ultimately involved moving 1.72 million cu m of earth.
</P>
<P>
Part of the project involved work on landslide-prone sections,
which covered 86 km in the middle and lower reaches of the river
and which were effectively dealt with.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
