<HEADLINE> Funding for Mausoleum Repairs in Inner Mongolia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, April 6 (Xinhua) -- China has put more than three
million yuan into renovating a mausoleum of Genghis Khan, the
Mongolian-born emperor of China's Yuan Dynasty in the 13th century.
</P>
<P>
The repair project is part of observances of the 50th
anniversary of north China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region and
is scheduled to be completed before June 20, according to the
director of the bureau in charge.
</P>
<P>
Genghis Khan, who was born in 1162, united the various
Mongolian tribes in 1206 and set up a powerful empire, referred to
as the Yuan Dynasty (1271 --1368) in Chinese history.
</P>
<P>
The work will include building a statue of the horse-riding
emperor in front of the steps leading up to the mausoleum, a
sacrificial altar, and a house for sacrificial offerings and
storing sacrificial utensils.
</P>
<P>
Eight hectares of pine trees and 10,000 square meters of grass
will be planted around the mausoleum. Antiques will be duplicated
as part of the mausoleum's display.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has spent nearly 10 million yuan on
repairs of the imperial mausoleum since 1955, when it was built,
said the director.
</P>
<P>
The mausoleum is a major historical and cultural site under
state protection, and has more than 120,000 visitors a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
