<HEADLINE> Education Center To Be Named for Chinese Warship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, April 6 (Xinhua) -- An education center named for the
cruiser "Chungshan" is planned for a shipyard near Wuhan, the
capital of central China's Hubei Province, at an estimated cost of
five million yuan (about 600,000 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The 20,000-square-meter center will have two exhibition halls
for historic relics and ship models, an 8.8-meter-high monument
beside the restored cruiser, and 25 steles describing crew members
of the cruiser.
</P>
<P>
Wang Zhongren, an official in charge of preparations, said that
young people can learn about military affairs and patriotism at
the center, and there will be courses on making model ships.
</P>
<P>
The Cruiser, named after Dr. Sun Yat-sen (Sun Chungshan),
forerunner of the Chinese Democratic Revolution, was sunk at Wuhan
October 24, 1938 in China's War of Resistance Against Japan.
</P>
<P>
It was salvaged on January 28. The 62.1-meter-long,
8.9-meter-wide, 780-ton cruiser played a role in an historical
event, following Chiang Kai-shek's betrayal of the revolution,
when he launched a surprise attack on the Chinese Communist Party
on March 20, 1926.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the center is scheduled to be completed in
mid-May.  
</P>
</TEXT>
