<HEADLINE> Chinese Expressway Re-routed To Protect Ancient City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, April 6 (Xinhua) -- An expressway that will run
from north to south China had to be redesigned recently to protect
the original site of an ancient city in Hebei Province in the
north.
</P>
<P>
The expressway starts in Beijing and ends in Shenzhen in
Guangdong Province on the Hong Kong border, and was originally
designed to run through Yecheng, the seat of 22 dynastic rulers
for more than 370 years from the early third century to the late
sixth century. The site in today's Linzhang County was designated
as a historical place under special state protection by the State
Council in 1988.
</P>
<P>
After the construction work started, the provincial cultural
relics department and the Linzhang County authorities submitted a
proposal to the State Bureau of Cultural Relics and the provincial
road construction headquarters, saying that the expressway should
be routed around Linzhang. The Ministry of Communications soon
revised the route to move it 600 meters west of the site. This
meant that two km were added to the highway, resulting in a cost
increase of two million yuan.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the Ministry of Communications spent more
than three million yuan excavating the area that was to be the
roadbed, and 213 ancient tombs, 20 kilns, and more than 3,000
pieces of cultural relics dating back as much as 2,000 years ago
were uncovered. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
