<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Earthquakes Jolt Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 6 (Xinhua) -- An earthquake measuring 6.4 on the
Richter Scale hit northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
Region around noon today. There are no deaths reported by the
press time.
</P>
<P>
According to reports from China's seismological network, the
quake, which hit at 12:36 (Beijing Time), had an the epicenter at
39.6 north latitude, 76.9 east longitude in Jiashi County, Kashi
Prefecture, in the westernmost part of Xinjiang.
</P>
<P>
Sources said that an earthquake measuring 6.3 on the Richter
Scale shook the county earlier in the day, at 7:46 a.m.
</P>
<P>
A series of after-shocks, the biggest measuring 4.8, jolted the
county after the first quake.
</P>
<P>
An official with the Xinjiang Seismology Bureau said that 14
people had reported injuries, five of them were in serious
condition. Thousands of houses were destroyed.
</P>
<P>
No other details are available at the present time, but the
official said that, thanks to pre-quake predictions, there are no
known deaths so far.
</P>
<P>
On March 20, an earthquake measuring 6.9 hit Jiashi, killing 24
people and injuring 40.  
</P>
</TEXT>
