<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila to Consult With US on Pork Trade Tiff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 6 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines hopes to peacefully
settle its pork trade tiff with the United States, the Philippine
News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The agency said Philippine Agriculture Secretary Salvador
Escudero had set the date for formal consultations with the U.S.
on April 10.
</P>
<P>
Escudero was quoted as saying that the U.S. had lodged a case
before the World Trade Organization (WTO), accusing Manila of
"deliberately slowing down" the process of importing U.S. pork and
poultry.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines was given a tariff-rate quota of 36,000 metric
tons of U.S. pork and poultry according to the minimum access
volume under the WTO-General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade.
</P>
<P>
However, the country did not import any until 1996, prompting
the U.S. to file the complaint and request the Philippines'
tariff-rate quota on pork and poultry take place within 30 days.
</P>
<P>
Escudero explained that there was no barriers for the imports
of U.S. products, but the Filipinos just don't like the taste of
frozen U.S. meat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
