<HEADLINE> Inflation Stands at 26.1 Percent in Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Iran's central bank announced
here today that the inflation rate stood at 26.1 percent during
the first 11 months of the last Iranian calendar year ending
March 20, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank of Iran (CBI) said in a report that the
average retail price index went up by 26.1 percent compared with
the same period of the preceding year.
</P>
<P>
The CBI report said that the average price index of goods and
consumer services went up by 23.8 percent, reaching 455.7 points
during the period.
</P>
<P>
It said that the average price index of goods and consumer
services for the capital city of Tehran was 447.4 points, up by
22.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Inflation is one of the major problems in Iran, which has
aroused wide complaints from the public. Specialists believe
that the official inflation rate is too low. The inflation
should be round 50 percent at present, they noted.
</P>
<P>
Saturday, the Iranian government raised prices of all oil
products, including super petrol and fuel oil, by a quarter
throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
Iran raised the fuel prices by 50 percent last year, 100
percent the previous year. The move triggered some protests and
demonstrations from the public, who complained about the
runaway inflation.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after the increase in fuel prices, all taxi drivers
today raised the taxi fare by a quarter or one-third in
Tehran. 
</P>
</TEXT>
