<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO to Fight Infectious Diseases in East </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUNIS, April 6 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization (WHO)
has worked out, in collaboration with member states, a regional
plan to fight newly-emerging infectious diseases, according to
reports reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
A report published by the WHO's East Mediterranean Bureau on
the occasion of the World Health Day, which falls on April 7,
said that the plan includes systems for observing diseases,
monitoring epidemics and promoting health consciousness in all
countries of the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the geographic position of the region and
its proximity to several regions where infectious diseases abound,
make it easy to be subject to the transfer of epidemics and
infectious diseases.
</P>
<P>
The high population density and the environmental and economic
conditions of some areas in the region, makes it easy for any
infectious disease to spread out so as to develop into an
epidemic.
</P>
<P>
It said that AIDS, malaria, viral hepatitis tuberculosis, viral
bleeding fever, cholera, and diseases of animal origin are among
the infectious diseases that the east Mediterranean population
is suffering from. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
