<HEADLINE> British Climber to Scale Tall Mountains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 6 (Xinhua) -- British climber Alan Hinkes who
wants to scale tall mountains without using oxygen was headed
Sunday for the world's fourth tallest peak.
</P>
<P>
Hinkes, a 42-year-old mountain guide from Yorkshire, plans to
climb Mount Lhotse by early next month. That's part of his plan to
climb 14 mountains that are over 8,000 meters high.
</P>
<P>
He already has climbed eight of them in the last nine years.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Hinkes left for Lukla in the Qomolangma region on
his way to the Khumbu Glacier to make his final attempt on Mount
Lhotse, which is 8,511 meters high.
</P>
<P>
After climbing Mount Lhotse he will climb two other peaks in
the region before going to Pakistan to attempt the Nanga Parbat
peak. He will then come back to Nepal and climb two more peaks.
</P>
</TEXT>
