<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> APEC Finance Ministers' Meeting Ends in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CEBU, The Philippines, April 6 (Xinhua) -- The fourth Asia
Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) finance ministers' meeting
ended here today with promises to facilitate private sector
participation in infrastructure development in the region.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement issued at the end of the two-day meeting,
the finance ministers also promised to promote the development of
domestic financial and capital markets in the region.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, the finance ministers agreed on a
set of voluntary principles for facilitating private sector
participation in infrastructure and promoting capital and
financial markets development.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to implement a series of collective
initiatives proposed by some APEC members on private sector
participation in infrastructure and the development of capital
markets.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the finance ministers exchanged views with
officials of the International Monetary Fund on macroeconomic
issues and policies for supporting freer flow of capital.
</P>
<P>
They also had a dialogue with representatives from two private
sector groups, the APEC Financiers Group and the Pacific Economic
Cooperation Council (PECC).
</P>
<P>
The next APEC finance ministers' meeting will be held next year
in Canada to review the progress in promoting financial and
capital markets development and absorbing private capital in
infrastructure projects. Canada currently holds the rotating
presidency of APEC.
</P>
<P>
The APEC was established in 1989 in response to the growing
interdependence among the Asia-Pacific economies. It groups China,
the United States, Australia, Brunei, Canada, Chile, Hong Kong,
Indonesia, Japan, South Korea, Singapore, Chinese Taipei,
Thailand, New Zealand, Malaysia, Papua New Guinea, Mexico and the
Philippines.  
</P>
</TEXT>
