<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK To Spot-check Access for Disabled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 6 (Xinhua) -- The Equal Opportunities
Commission (EOC) will check more than 100 buildings at random
throughout Hong Kong next month to ensure their facilities for
the disabled are being used properly, Hong Kong Standard reported
today.
</P>
<P>
There was inadequate access to some facilities in public
buildings, a commission spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
Places where the disabled visit frequently, such as Government
buildings, food outlets, shopping arcades, commercial buildings
and multi-purpose complexes, will be prime targets, Cheung
Kin-fai, of the Rehabilitation Alliance Hong Kong, said, whose
team will make the checks.
</P>
<P>
And general access and specially-designed toilets for the
disabled will be emphasized, Cheung added.
</P>
<P>
"We think we will be able to check 10 locations a day, and
expect to finish the whole project within two weeks," he said.
</P>
<P>
Although many facilities for the disabled had been installed,
they were not being used properly, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said the alliance sought help from the commission because
the lack of access for the disabled was a form of discrimination.
"Under the principle of equal opportunities among all people, the
disabled should have free access to the buildings." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
