<HEADLINE> "Save the Peace" Rally Held In Tel Aviv </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 6 (Xinhua) -- A huge mass rally took
place in Tel Aviv's Rabin Square Saturday night with a call to
"Save the Peace."
</P>
<P>
Thousands of people gathered in the place where the late
Israeli prime minister Yitzhak Rabin was gunned down by an
ultra-right student on November 4, 1995 at the end of a peace
rally.
</P>
<P>
The after-Shabbat (Israel's weekly day-off) rally was
organized at a time when the Israeli-Palestinian relations fell
into an unprecedented deep crisis since the Oslo Accord in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Shimon Peres, chairman of the opposition Labor Party and
former prime minister after Rabin, lashed out at Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu in an emotional address, saying that since the
his election, "10 months have passed, and the peace looks weak
and security has been undermined."
</P>
<P>
The Labor chief warned of the consequences of the halt of the
peace process. He noted that it means Israel's isolation and arms
race.
</P>
<P>
Peres, architect of the Oslo Accords, said that the whole mood
will change considerably and old confrontation will re-emerge
consequently.
</P>
<P>
The rally was initiated by the peace body "An Entire Generation
Demands Peace" and supported by other peace and youth movements in
Israel. The country's best singers volunteered to perform at the
rally.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the peace activists said that they held the
rally to protest the deterioration of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The statement asserted "A whole generation will not allow
anybody to bury the peace process. We have no other process, we
have no other peace, we have no other future."
</P>
<P>
"We must go back to the road of peace, to the road of Yitzhak
Rabin," declared the statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
