<BODY>
<HEADLINE> APEC Launches Computerized Information Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CEBU, The Philippines, April 6 (Xinhua) -- A computerized
information network was set up among the 18 APEC (Asia Pacific
Economic Cooperation) member economies' finance ministries this
morning when computer systems of these ministries were formally
linked.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the two-day APEC finance ministers' meeting,
Japanese Finance Minister Hiroshi Matsuzuka personally linked the
computer systems of these finance ministries through a computer.
</P>
<P>
This information network was proposed by Japan and endorsed by
the third APEC finance ministers' meeting in Kyoto last year. The
APEC Finance Ministries homepage was offered by Singapore.
</P>
<P>
With the establishment of the network, the economic and
financial authorities of APEC member economies can share
information about overall economic developments in the region.
</P>
<P>
The network will also facilitate the dissemination of
macroeconomic and financial information to the public via bulletin
boards on the Internet, and provide guidance for investors.
</P>
<P>
The APEC, established in 1989, groups China, the United States,
Japan, Singapore, Australia, Mexico, Thailand, Chinese Taipei, New
Zealand, Canada, South Korea, Brunei, Malaysia, Indonesia, Hong
Kong, the Philippines, Papua New Guinea and Chile. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
