<DOCNO> XIE19970406.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot Exports Up in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus' total exports increased
by 14.4 percent last year compared with 1995, according to a
report by the Department of Statistics and Research available
today.
</P>
<P>
Total exports increased from 555.6 million Cyprus
pounds (1,111.2 million U.S. dollars) in 1995 to 649 million
pounds (1,298 million dollars) last year, but the report noted
that domestic exports in fact dropped while re-exports
increased.
</P>
<P>
The report said the European Union countries absorbed 77.2
percent or 126.6 million Cyprus pounds (about 250 million
dollars) of Cyprus domestic exports in 1996. The Arab countries
followed with a share of 19.8 percent compared with 18 percent
in 1995.
</P>
<P>
However, the island's imports also increased from
1,670 million pounds (about 3,340 million dollars) in 1995 to
1,857 million pounds (3,714 million dollars) last year.
</P>
<P>
The year 1996 ended with a crude deficit of 1,208 million
pounds (2,416 million dollars) compared with the 1995 deficit of
1,114 million pounds (2,228 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
According to the report, major imports are home consumption
goods, transport equipment and capital goods, while major
exports are industrial products of domestic produce, mainly
clothing and footwear, as well as agricultural products.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970406.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chimpanzee Population Decreases in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 6 (Xinhua) -- The population of Ugandan
chimpanzees has fallen from 10,000 in 1986 to only 3,000 at
present, reported the local daily "the Monitor" today.
</P>
<P>
The decline has brought the usually timid primate into the
category of "seriously endangered species" in Uganda today, the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
Mr. Robinson Yampa, animal keeper of the Uganda Wildlife
Centre at the Entebbee zoo, 40 km south of Kampala was quoted as
saying that the others in the seriously endangered category
include the parrot and the rhinoceros in the country.
</P>
<P>
The increasing spate of deforestation is the major reason for
the decline, he said.
</P>
<P>
Poaching is another reason for the decline, he said, adding
that chimpanzee smugglers and poachers have been arrested on
several occasions and have been prosucuted in the country.
</P>
<P>
Chimpanzee and other seriously endangered species in Uganda
are important elements for attracking tourists to the country and
are playing an important role in tourism in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
