<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Nepal's Bitter-Sweet Access to Information </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Tourists from western countries
often found to their surprise that there are almost as many
computer service companies as travel agencies in downtown streets
of this capital city of Nepal.
</P>
<P>
Despite one of the poorest countries in the World, the
Himalayan kingdom of Nepal has caught up the latest development of
information technology and has access to the worldwide
computer-based communication network -- the Internet.
</P>
<P>
With the country's other sectors growing by less than five
percent in recently years, the turnout of the computer-related
industry is surging at an annual growth rate of over 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
Many businesses of the tourism sector as well as Nepal-based
international organizations and aid agencies quickly opened their
cyber addresses on the Internet when a local private company
initiated the Internet service here three years ago.
</P>
<P>
Travel agencies in Nepal have realized the importance to lure
foreign visitors through advertising the country's picturesque
Himalayan peaks, exotic cultural heritage and hospitable people in
a multimedia way on the Net.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that there are already over 22,000 sites on the
Internet established for disseminating messages about Nepal or
matters related to the country, according to local daily the
Kathmandu Post.
</P>
<P>
Although many of these Net sites have been created by Nepali
students studying abroad or foreign tourists sharing their
adventures in Nepal, computer service companies here saw a
favorite prospect of the tourism-driven Internet business for
local clients and are scrambling to begin their networking
service.
</P>
<P>
Earlier the Tourism Ministry of Nepal has set up its own home
page on the Internet in order to promote the government's "Visit
Nepal 1998" program, which is aimed at attracting some 500,000
foreign tourists in the year.
</P>
<P>
Kathmandu's media circles also showed their enthusiasm for the
Internet as almost all English-language daily and weekly papers,
including the official daily the Rising Nepal, have launched their
cyber editions.
</P>
<P>
The state-owned Radio Nepal linked up with the Internet last
week to bring its English news broadcasts to listeners around the
World.
</P>
<P>
However, compared with their counterparts in developed
countries, Internet users in Nepal have to pay relatively high
rates -- at least several hundreds US dollars for one year's
service.
</P>
<P>
At present, Nepal's Internet service companies depend on the
satellite channels of the state-run Nepal Telecommunication
Corporation (NTC) to transmit and receive Internet signals, mainly
contributing to their hefty operation costs, industry sources
said.
</P>
<P>
According to an official of the Mercantile Office System
Company, the first Internet service provider in the country, the
price of using the Internet has gone down about 80 percent in the
last one and half years.
</P>
<P>
If the communication costs could be cut down further, more
customers would apply for the Internet access, he said, adding
that the number of Internet users in the country is expected to
grow 40 percent every year.
</P>
<P>
He added that his company had a plan to establish a national
network to provide Internet service to users outside the capital
city and had already set up a service station in a tourist
destination in West Nepal.
</P>
<P>
But local users have no reason to expect a considerable price
decrease for the Internet service in the near future as the
government seems unwilling to break the state-run NTC's monopoly
over communication links and allow private companies to install
their own satellite receivers, service providers said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
