<HEADLINE> Singaporeans Gamble Away Around 3.5 Billion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Singaporeans gambled away around
five billion Singapore dollars, or about 3.5 billion US dollars,
last year, putting the city-state of three million people at the
top in Southeast Asia in terms of per capita spending on gambling.
</P>
<P>
According to a report in the Sunday Times, the Sunday edition
of the Straits Times, today, that amount was just what was placed
on legal bets, while billions more went to illegal betting
syndicates, and an unknown amount was spent by Singaporeans in
casinos in Genting Highlands of Malaysia, Australia and other
places, including on cruise ships.
</P>
<P>
It said that last year's estimated total spent on legal
gambling was up from 4.2 billion Singapore dollars (about three
billion US dollars) in 1995. The money went to horse racing,
4-digits, jackpot machines, as well as on the Singapore Sweep and
Toto.
</P>
<P>
However, the report said that gaming industry officials
estimated that the turnover for illegal betting in Singapore could
be around 20 billion Singapore dollars, or about 14 billion US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Only last month, the police smashed one syndicate which netted
an estimated 2.4 million Singapore dollars (about 1.7 million US
dollars) a month. Police believe that there are one or two more
such groups still operating.  
</P>
</TEXT>
