<HEADLINE> China To Make Health Food Standards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 6 (Xinhua) -- China has approved state standards
for health food, which will take effect on May 1, 1997, according
to the State Bureau of Technical Supervision.
</P>
<P>
The standards define and classify health foods, and include
technical requirements, testing procedures, and regulations on
labelling.
</P>
<P>
Health food products are classified in 13 categories according
to their effect on the body, and technical requirments state that
health food must enhance human health in at least one way.
</P>
<P>
An additional three contents are to be added to labels of
health products, giving nutrition information and function of the
products, and specific contents.
</P>
<P>
Health food is distinctly different from drugs, and is not
designed or produced for treating illness. The health food
industry has developed rapidly in China in the 1990s, and the
adoption of state standards for health food marks the beginning of
putting production, distribution, and management of the industry
under the control of laws. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970406.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China City Increasing Pollution-Control Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Weihai City, in east China's
Shandong province, is watching its environmental protection more
closely while its economy develops rapidly.
</P>
<P>
The city closed a paper mill recently even though the mill had
over seven million yuan in net profits in 1994.
</P>
<P>
"After the shut-down of the mill, the surrounding ecology
improved remarkably, with many fish and shrimps returning to the
nearby sea waters," one expert noted.
</P>
<P>
The city's hi-tech development zone has turned down over 10 big
projects with a total investment of 2.2 billion yuan over the past
five years because of potential pollution problems. And the city
has spent some 120 million yuan on two sewage treatment plants,
each with a capacity of treating 80,000 tons of waste water
daily. Urban sewage is expected to be totally under control this
year, according to experts here.
</P>
<P>
Weihai has also increased efforts at developing solar energy to
reduce pollution caused by burning coal.
</P>
<P>
The city has spent some 1.3 billion yuan on environmental
protection infrastructure construction, and moved 38 polluters,
and shut down two ironworks, three paper mills, and four
electroplating plants.The government has drafted more than 10
environmental protection regulations, giving its environmental
protection department the right to turn down any construction
project application.
</P>
<P>
The city government rejected 53 projects with potential
pollution problems, and examined over 60 cases that violated the
Environmental Protection Law during the 1991-1995 period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
