<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Global Alert on Emerging Infectious </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 6 (Xinhua) -- "Emerging infectious diseases -
global alert, global response." This is the theme chosen by the
World Health Organization (WHO) to mark this year's World Health
Day which falls on April 7.
</P>
<P>
WHO's warning is not from imagination. In the past decades,
spectacular progress has been made with a number of infectious
diseases, like smallpox, eradicated. However, tragically, with
optimism came a false sense of security, which has helped many
diseases spread with alarming rapidity.
</P>
<P>
According to information from WHO, in the last 20 years, more
than 30 new and highly infectious diseases have been identified.
they include the virulent Ebola-type hemorrhagicc fever,
HIV/AIDS, and hepatitis C and D.
</P>
<P>
Other examples of new or newly detected infectious diseases of
global concern include a new form of cholera, a naemolytic
uraemic syndrome, Legionaires' disease, and lyme disease.
</P>
<P>
There is also a highly fatal respiratory disease caused by a
virus called sin nombre, a variant of Creutzfeldt-Jokob disease
of central nervous system which is suspected, though not proven,
to be associated with a similar disease in cattle called bovine
spongiform encephalopathy.
</P>
<P>
WHO maintains that although it is not always possible to know
if these are new in humans, or whether they have been present but
unrecognized throughout the years, many8emerging diseases are
thought to be due to a closer contact of man with their
reservoirs in nature, with a successful "jump" of the infectious
agent from animal to man across the species.
</P>
<P>
For many of these diseases there is no treatment, cure or
vaccine, according to the World Health Organization.
</P>
<P>
A WHO press release says re-emerging infectious diseases often
reappear in epidemic proportions.
</P>
<P>
Tuberculosis is increasing worldwide due in part to its close
association with HIV infection; cholera has been re-introduced
into countries and continents where it has previously
disappeared, and where it can spread because water and sanitation
systems have deteriorated.
</P>
<P>
Besides, dengue or "break-boneathy" fever has started to occur in
urban areas where mosquito control has broken down.
</P>
<P>
In addition, microorganisms resistant to antibiotic drugs
emerged and spread soon after the introduction of these drugs and
in parallel with their use.
</P>
<P>
Many well-known antibiotics are no longer effective to treat
common infections such as otitis, pneumonia, gonorrhoea and
tuberculosis.
</P>
<P>
In his message to mark the World Health Day, WHO Director
General Hiroshi Nakajima says, "We have to face the fact that
infectious diseases are a common threat which demands urgent
attention, especially at a time when people all over the world
are being brought closer together by international travel and
trade."
</P>
<P>
He called for a global alert, saying, "communicable diseases
respect no frontier. We must work together globally to control
them." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970406.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-06 </DATE_TIME>
