<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Fight Foreign Dumping with Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 6 (Xinhua) -- China now has legal power to
protect its manufacturers after enacting its first anti-dumping
and anti-subsidies regulations.
</P>
<P>
The new regulations, drafted mainly according to rules of the
World Trade Organization (WTO), enable China to take action
against foreign companies that export products at lower than
normal prices to China, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
The regulations stipulate the investigation procedures and
rulings on dumping and subsidy actions.
</P>
<P>
China intends to stop foreign companies from threatening the
competitiveness of Chinese industries, from causing substantial
damage or preventing the establishment of relevant industries.
</P>
<P>
Shang Ming, an official with the Ministry of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC), said that foreign dumping cost
China billions of US dollars and several thousand jobs a year.
</P>
<P>
Moftec and several other departments are in charge of
anti-dumping and anti-subsidy issues from appeals to verdicts.
</P>
<P>
Companies appealing dumping charges must represent a
considerable proportion of the total domestic output of a certain
product.
</P>
<P>
China will levy anti-dumping or anti-subsidy duties after a
verdict is announced that dumping or subsidies exist and have
caused substantial damage.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
