<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Enhance Ocean Exploration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Two Chinese prospecting ships are
scheduled to leave for the northern Pacific Ocean on May 20 to
spend six months exploring the seabed with robots that can work
6,000 meters under water.
</P>
<P>
This is one of four scheduled large-scale prospecting events
this century, an official from the China Ocean Mineral Research
and Development Association said in today's China Daily. He said
as the economy maintains its sustained and rapid growth, China has
an ever-growing demand for minerals.
</P>
<P>
In addition to exploring natural resources in international
waters, China is tapping the natural wealth in a
three-million-square-kilometer area it controls according to the
UN Sea Convention Law.
</P>
<P>
More than 20 billion tons of petroleum await development in
China's subsea areas, where other resources also abound.
</P>
<P>
China will start a high-tech program to develop marine
resources. The program, with the goal of becoming a technical
resource for the maritime industry, will involve three major
sectors: sea water prospecting, marine biology and submarine oil
exploration.
</P>
<P>
In the next 15 years, China plans to vigorously develop its
technology in seafood breeding, marine pharmaceuticals, marine
chemicals and sea water utilization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
