<HEADLINE> Inflation to Drop Below Two Percent in Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Italy's annual inflation rate this
month could dip below two percent for the first time in 28 years,
said Industry Minister Pierluigi Bersani today.
</P>
<P>
On Monday the national statistics institute ISTAT is expected
to confirm that the inflation rate in March fell to 2.2 percent
from February's 2.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
In a report prepared for parliament, Ciampi said the
anti-inflation process is expected to be consolidated in the
course of 1997, making it possible to achieve the goal of keeping
the average annual rate below the planned 2.5 percent level and
the monthly figures below two percent in the first six months.
</P>
<P>
Optimism about the inflation trend helped raise the value of
the lira on the foreign exchange market yesterday, and also
boosted the bond futures market.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said speculation was growing over a possible new cut
in official interest rates. The central bank's discount rate has
been steady at 6.75 percent since January. 
</P>
