<HEADLINE> China's Insurance Market to Open Gradually </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 6 (Xinhua) -- The opening of China's insurance
market will be gradual, prudent and orderly since the market is
still in an early stage, an official of the People's Bank of China
said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign companies are allowed to sell life insurance in China
through joint ventures, the official was quoted by today's China
Daily as saying.
</P>
<P>
The annual premium income of foreign insurers last year was 575
million yuan (69.2 million US dollars), accounting for 0.74
percent of the country's total.
</P>
<P>
The country started allowing foreign companies to operate in
China on a trial basis in 1992 when the American International
Group received a license to operate in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The introduction of foreign insurers is aimed at promoting the
reform and development of China's insurance industry.
</P>
<P>
To enhance the central bank's supervision over foreign
insurance companies, the central bank has revised the Shanghai
provisional regulations on foreign insurance institutions. The
revised regulation is waiting for the final approval of the State
Council. It would regulate all foreign insurers' activities.
</P>
<P>
The insurance industry this year will concentrate on the
establishment of a State reinsurance company, reform of
agricultural insurance and export credit insurance, the paper
says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
