<HEADLINE> Qinghua University Develops Electric Vehicles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Four minivans powered by
electricity have been developed in Qinghua University, one of the
most important talent banks in China.
</P>
<P>
They are from the joint effort of the university's automobile
engineering department and more than ten manufacturing and
research units as a national research project, which was approved
by the State Planning Commission in 1992 and completed last
May. Achievements included electric vehicle batteries, battery
management systems and chargers.
</P>
<P>
The vehicles can be recharged overnight during non-peak
hours. However, electric vehicles in China will be heavier, slower
and limited to traveling short distances, according to today's
China Daily, explaining that since high-power hydro-nickle
batteries are too expensive, only low-density power lead-acid
batteries are practical in China.
</P>
<P>
The electric minivan's maximum speed is about 80 km per hour,
and the range per charge is about 120 km.
</P>
<P>
Two prototypes of electric minibuses traveled 6,000 km outside
Beijing last year. A fixed route for the minivans might be opened
between Qinghua University and a community where many professors
live.
</P>
<P>
Besides electric minbuses, postal vehicles, milk and meal
distributive vehicles and airport shuttles are expected to be
powered by lead-acid batteries.
</P>
<P>
The State Commission for Science, Technology and Industry for
National Defence, co-operating with US aerospace firm Northrop
Grumman Co, developed an electric bus last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
