<HEADLINE> Central China Province Increasing Efforts To Fight Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Central China's Henan Province has
announced that all sources of pollution in the Huaihe River valley
must be treated to meet government standards by the end of this
year.
</P>
<P>
Of the province's 566 major polluters, over 100 are expected to
be able to set up pollution treatment facilities, and 90 percent
of the polluters are expected to meet government-set discharge
standards by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
The State Council, the country's highest governing body,
announced last year that all polluters in the river valley should
meet government discharge standards by the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The province has 1,045 heavy polluters in the valley, 566 of
which each discharges more than a hundred tons of waste water
daily.
</P>
<P>
"Some 3.2 billion yuan (about 400 million US dollars) is
expected to be spent making these factories meet the discharge
standards," said an official with the provincial government, who
noted that industrial waste can be reduced by more than 70 percent
if they all meet the standards.
</P>
<P>
The province closed 17,000 small polluters last year, and all
cities and towns have cut pollution by 10 percent, according to
official statistics.
</P>
<P>
The provincial environmental protection bureau has made regular
inspections of the major polluters, supervising their efforts and
urging them to speed up treatment.
</P>
<P>
In addition, governments at all levels have been closely
watching new projects, strictly preventing potential pollution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
