<HEADLINE> South China City to Step up Distribution Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 6 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangzhou city, a
leader in the country's opening up process, plans to improve the
distribution sector this year by placing priority on helping
enterprises eliminate losses and increase profits, and on
promoting the merger of firms.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent conference on distribution, by 1998, the
debt-incurring rate of 13 large commercial groups will drop to
some 65 percent from 1995's 70 percent and that of 106 small
businesses to around 80 percent from 1995's 96 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, during the Ninth Five-Year-Plan, the city will set
up 13 large enterprise groups in the commercial sector, each with
properties worth 250 million yuan and a sales volume of over 5
billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Small firms will be given more freedom to act on their own and
a stock-issuing system will be tried out on 38 small firms, which
allows employees to own shares while others are available to the
public.
</P>
<P>
Another 20 small companies will be revitalized by being leased
or operated on a contract basis, and those with several years of
experience of losses will be allowed to declare bankruptcy or to
be mergered. 
</P>
</TEXT>
