<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgrade Raps U.S. Interference in Others' Internal Affairs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, April 5 (Xinhua) -- A major Yugoslav newspaper,
"Politika," today condemned the United States for openly
interfering in the internal affairs of other countries.
</P>
<P>
Political leaders in the U.S. have recently attacked other
countries for "having influenced" U.S. general elections, but
facts show that it is the U.S. that has overtly meddled in other
countries' internal affairs, the newspaper said in a signed
article.
</P>
<P>
The article said the U.S. Congress each year allocates a large
amount of money to influence other countries' politics, and this
has become an open secret.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the U.S. government set up an agency some 15 years
ago to "promote democracy" in other countries, spending some 3
million dollars each year to back political parties, trade unions,
dissidents and news media it favored, so as to influence the
political situation in these countries, the article said.
</P>
<P>
The agency of the U.S. government openly financed certain trade
unions in France, Paraguay, the Philippines and Panama, and in the
1980s, granted some 5 million dollars to Polish people living in
the U.S. to support the "Solidarity Trade Union," the article
noted.
</P>
<P>
It has also exerted influence on the political activities of
the "mild parties" in Portugal, Costa Rica, Bolivia and Northern
Ireland, it added.
</P>
<P>
It is widely known that in 1990, the agency donated 400,000
dollars to a party in the Czech Republic that backed Vaclav Havel
for presidency, and provided Nicaragua with 3 million dollars in
"technical assistance" to help the U.S.-favored candidate to win
the elections, the article said.
</P>
<P>
It said that in 1996, the agency spent some 1.6 million dollars
to draft a plan to carry out political propaganda directed at
China, so as to "intensify U.S. influence in China and Asia."
</P>
<P>
The agency's activities to interfere in other countries'
internal affairs, nevertheless, were dwarfed by those of the
U.S. Central Intelligence Agency (CIA), which often secretly
plotted to topple or prop up a political figure in other
countries, the article said.
</P>
<P>
It noted that the CIA even supported selected political parties
in "friendly" nations of the United States.
</P>
<P>
The CIA also spread rumors, bought off political leaders, and
spent millions and millions of dollars to control the media of a
certain country, the article noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970406.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Cleaning Up Its Major River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 6 (Xinhua) -- China's biggest economic center
has decided to clean the Suzhou River, that runs through the urban
area, to make it suitable for tourism and sight-seeing, a
municipal government official says.
</P>
<P>
The water quality of the river has deteriorated since the
middle part of the century when a large number of factories and
residential areas were built along its banks, and large amounts of
industrial and residential waste water was directly discharged
into it.
</P>
<P>
Since the late '60s, the river has turned black and gives off
an awful odor.
</P>
<P>
In the late '80s, the city laid a large pipe on the river's
northern bank to handle waste water in the 70-sq.km. area, which
discharges the water into the Yangtze River after being
treated. The system's daily capacity is 1.4 million tons.
</P>
<P>
"Now waste water is no longer directly discharged into the
river, and the water quality is improving," said the official.
</P>
<P>
However, because the causes of river pollution are many and
complex and the pollution has gone on for quite a long time, the
river is still black and still smells bad.
</P>
<P>
A major group supporting the clean-river project has been set
up, headed by the mayor, and the city has decided that no solid
matter, or oil or other substances should be found floating on the
river surface after October 1 of this year, and that structures
that do not have permits must be dismantled.
</P>
<P>
Some 29 docks will be moved this year, according to the
official.
</P>
<P>
The Asian Development Bank plans to help the city clean up the
river, and some overseas Chinese have expressed a wish to donate
to the project, the official said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
