<HEADLINE> Cohen Says U.S. to Maintain Strong Presence in Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 5 (Xinhua) -- The United States will keep a
significant military presence in Asia even if there will be a
peaceful reunification of the Korean peninsula, U.S. Defense
Secretary William Cohen said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Cohen was making the remarks in Honolulu, Hawaii, on his way to
Japan and South Korea for a two-day visit, designed to highlight
the U.S. commitment to maintaining a large troop presence in the
region.
</P>
<P>
"We will still have to maintain a significant presence in the
region, we would still remain a strong presence in Korea," Cohen
said.
</P>
<P>
"We intend to remain in Korea, assuming there's a unification,
into the indefinite future," he added.
</P>
<P>
There are about 37,000 U.S. troops in South Korea, and 45,000
troops in Japan, which, with some troops stationed in other parts
of the region, totals up to 100,000.
</P>
<P>
Cohen's remarks indicate that the United States would never
relinquish its intention to flaunt its military strength in the
Asian-Pacific area to make sure its influence would not be dented.
</P>
<P>
This is Cohen's second trip abroad as defense secretary and
first to Asia. He told reporters he hoped to travel to China
before the end of the year in search of ways to establish more
regular U.S.-Chinese military contacts.
</P>
<P>
When he is in Japan and South Korea, he will meet government
and military officials of both countries and discuss a wide range
of security issues with them. He will also inspect American forces
in the field. 
</P>
</TEXT>
