<HEADLINE> China's Largest City Plans Pollution Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, April 6 (Xinhua) -- China's most populated and,
perhaps, most polluted city is planning to clean up its dirty
image in the next few years, municipal government sources say.
</P>
<P>
A "Green Program" campaign has begun this year to control the
heavy pollution of this city in southwest China, which is now the
fourth municipality that is directly under central government
control.
</P>
<P>
The city is one of China's oldest industrial centers and is
famous for its acid rain, and the 30 million people of the
newly-expanded urban area suffer from smoke, dust, and other
effluvia churned out by thousands of factories.
</P>
<P>
The clean-up program has 29 items that deal with polluted
water, gas, acid rain, and the environment as a whole, and are
expected to meet state criteria for pollution control by the year
2000, sources say.
</P>
<P>
The most noteworthy thing is the 300 factories that will
control water pollution, half of which will be built in the Three
Gorges reservoir area along the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing is regarded as a major place for improving the
Chinese economy in underdeveloped central and western regions, and
is a focal point of resettlement efforts for towns that will be
flooded by the Three Gorges Reservoir.
</P>
<P>
However, some experts say that the ambitious program will be a
hard job. Unlike Beijing, Tianjin and Shanghai, the other three
municipalities directly under central government control, all of
which are located on plains, Chongqing is a hilly city where
geographical and meteorological conditions make things more
difficult. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
