<HEADLINE> Over 30 Rebel Boats Destroyed In Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Over 30 Tamil "Sea Tiger" boats
were destroyed by the Sri Lankan Navy during the last one month,
according to Naval sources today.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that as a result of continuous attacks
launched since January 31 this year more than 100 "Sea Tigers" of
the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE), including several
"Sea Tiger" leaders, were also killed.
</P>
<P>
The biggest attack was on March 24 when a Navy flotilla
confronted a "Sea Tiger" flotilla of 25 boats in the east of
Mullativu in the Eastern Province.
</P>
<P>
This battle went on for four hours. Two rebel suicide boats
were destroyed, nearly 100 rebels were killed and at least 60
others injured in the attack.
</P>
<P>
The last attack was on April 1 when the navy boats observed 8
LTTE boats in Kakarativu in the east coast of the country. Two
rebel boats were destroyed with some rebels on board in the
attack.
</P>
<P>
A total of 35 LTTE boats have been destroyed since January this
year, according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE has been fighting against the Sri Lankan government
for a separate Tamil state in the north and east of the island
country since 1983. 
</P>
