<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, April 5 (Xinhua) -- The following are the latest
major cultural news items in Latin America:
</P>
<P>
1. Spanish Filmmaker to Shoot "Tango" Musical Film
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Spanish filmmaker Carlos Saura will start in
May the musical film "Tango" in Buenos Aires, which features the
most outstanding and diverse characteristics of the typical
Argentine dance.
</P>
<P>
The film, a conventional love story, presents some 400 tango
dancers, said Saura, who declined to confirm if the famous artist
Julio Bocca would star the film.
</P>
<P>
2. Montevideo to Have National Russian Theater Academy Branch
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- The Uruguayan capital will soon have a branch of
the National Russian Theater Academy, the most prestigious of its
kind in Europe, it was announced here today.
</P>
<P>
Sources close to the Uruguayan theater said the first courses
will include subjects of theater and cinematography.
</P>
<P>
The first course of the Academy, to be started by mid-1997,
will be coordinated by Valentin Tepliakov, director of the School
of Acting in the Russian Academy.
</P>
<P>
3. Costa Rican Cultural Community Suffers Great Loss
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- The death of poet Isaac Felipe Azofeifa and
novelist Fabian Dobles in less than ten days dealt a heavy blow to
the cultural community of Costa Rica, which lost two great masters
who created an epoch in the country during the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
Azofeifa, 87, who had been paralyzed for 11 months because of a
stroke, died Wednesday after a pneumonia attack.
</P>
<P>
Zofeifa was the author of many important works, such as "Vigil
at the Feet of Death," "Seasons," and "Days and Territories." His
last masterpiece was "Orbit."
</P>
<P>
4. French Photographer to Exhibit in Colombia
</P>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA -- French photographer Janca will open an
exhibition here to show her best works, including some 20
photographs with themes related to sex, religion, and symbols.
</P>
<P>
The show will open on April 12 and end on May 16.
</P>
<P>
5. Photographic Exhibition on China Opens in Brasilia
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- An exhibition of more than 30 photographs that
demonstrate new changes in China was inaugurated here.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition, which was held in the Brazilian Foreign
Relations Ministry building, was sponsored by Brazilian actress
Lucia Santos.
</P>
<P>
6. International Artistic Meet to Be Held in Mexico
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- The Fourth Popular Art International Meeting,
sponsored by the Free Center of Theater and Arts Experimentation
(FCTAE), will start in Mexico City on April 17, sources close to
organizers said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, which will last till May 1, will be attended by
representatives from 16 countries, FCTAE representative Enrique
Cisneros said.
</P>
<P>
The event will consist of workshops, lectures, exhibitions,
video screenings, and a series of artistic shows.
</P>
<P>
7. Japanese Dance Captivates Nicaraguans
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- The Japanese dance ensemble "Ippei Fukuda"
captivated an avid Nicaraguan public in the Ruben Dario National
Theater.
</P>
<P>
The program, made of folkloric and contemporary dances,
marveled young people specially, who gave long applauses to the
Japanese artists synthesizing traditional and contemporaneous
elements of the Japanese scenic arts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
