<HEADLINE> Number of Senior People in Indonesia Increase Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 6 (Xinhua) -- The number of senior people in
Indonesia between 1990 and 2025 will increase by 414 percent, said
a lecturer at the medical faculty of the Diponegoro Univesity in
Semarang, Central Java, reports reaching here today said.
</P>
<P>
"This means, by 2025 there will be 20 million additional old
people in the country," said Prof. Dr. Boedhi Darmojo.
</P>
<P>
He also said the hike rate is the highest in the world compared
with Kenya's 347 percent, Brazil's 255 percent, India's 242
percent, China's 220 percent, Japan's 129 percent, Germany's 66
percent and Sweden's 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
"The growth in the number of old people is predicted to bring
Indonesia to the fifth or sixth rank in the list of countries with
the highest number of old people by 2000," Darmojo said, adding
that in 1980 Indonesia ranked the 10th."low quality" in the sense
that they have never experienced formal education as they live in
remote rural areas.
</P>
<P>
In the future, however, he expressed his optimism that the
country's old people will mainly comprise of the "quality" ones.
</P>
<P>
"This is just the logical consequence of the successful
development programs in the country which have also push up the
life expectancy of most of its people," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
