<HEADLINE> Canada, U.S. to Clash for Ice Hockey Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 5 (Xinhua) -- The United States defeated China
6-0 to enter the final of the World Women's Ice Hockey
Championship in Kitchener on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The United States, silver medalists in three previous worlds,
will clash Canada for the gold medal. Canada downed Finland 2-1
on an earlier match. China and Finland will play for the bronze.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese, who have a reputation for intense physical play,
had only 14 shots on U.S. goalie Erin Whitten. China's Guo Hong
had 32 saves.
</P>
<P>
Stephanie O'Sullivan of the U.S. team scored the opening goal
at 12:05 in the first period.
</P>
<P>
Looney assisted on that goal and on Tara Mounsey's late in the
period. She and Karyn Bye added goals late in the second, and
Laurie Baker and Gretchen Ulion scored early in the third.
</P>
<P>
In the early Canada-Finland match, Vicki Sunohara of Canada
scored with 24 seconds remaining to give Canada a fourth shot at
the title.
</P>
<P>
Canada never lost a game in any previous worlds on its way to
three gold medals.
</P>
<P>
Five of the eight teams competing will advance to the 1998
Olympics at Nagano, the first games to include women's ice hockey.
The host country, Japan, gets automatic entry.
</P>
<P>
The four teams playing Saturday earned Olympic berths in the
preliminary round, and Russia and Sweden will vie for the final
opening Sunday. Switzerland and Norway were eliminated Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
