<HEADLINE> Ukraine to Receive Loan From World Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, April 5 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank will give Ukraine the
second batch of a business development loan, media reports said
here today.
</P>
<P>
Tamara Solyanyk, deputy head of the National Agency of
Reconstruction and Development, was quoted as saying that the
World Bank's board of directors would take an official decision on
disbursing the second batch at its April 8 meeting.
</P>
<P>
But she did not say how much the second batch will be.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank is granting the loan for developing small and
medium-sized businesses in Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
Solyanyk said the disbursement of the second batch depends on
the bank's approval of Ukraine's report on the use of the first
batch of 100 million U.S. dollars, which was granted last
September.
</P>
<P>
World Bank Managing Director Caio Kokh-Wester, who visited Kiev
at the end of March, said that the bank had no serious objections
to the Ukrainian government's report.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine is hoping to use the second batch of the loan, along
with a European Union loan of 100 million dollars to service its
foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
The government said in March that Ukraine will have to spend
130 million dollars on servicing interests on loans from
international financial institutions and foreign governments.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine's foreign debt had risen to 8.725 billion dollars by
January 10 this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
