<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ten Million Infected with Hepatitis B Virus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 6 (Xinhua) -- About ten million people are
infected with the hepatitis b virus in Indonesia or about one in
ten of the country's 200 million people, a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
The best way to prevent hepatitis b infection was to immunize
infants as early as possible, Health Minister Sujudi said Saturday
when launching a nation-wide hepatitis b immunization program for
Indonesian babies in Bogor, west Java, reports reaching here today
said.
</P>
<P>
Sujudi said that 90 percent of the babies born from mothers
carrying the hepatitis b virus would also have the virus and this
would affect the quality of their lives later on.
</P>
<P>
To combat the disease, the government beginning this month was
providing free anti-hepatitis b vaccination to babies throughout
the country.
</P>
<P>
With the program, it is expected that Indonesia would free from
hepatitis b virus in 2019, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
