<HEADLINE> Gunmen Block Albanian Prime Minister's Convoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, April 5 (Xinhua) -- A group of unknown gunmen today
blocked a convoy of Albanian Prime Minister Bashkim Fino and his
cabinet ministers on their way to the northern town of Shkoder,
forcing them to return to Tirana.
</P>
<P>
The gunmen stood in the way of Fino's convoy at Bushat, a
village south of Shkoder, in the morning, shooting in the air and
throwing grenades to the roadside.
</P>
<P>
Fino and his ministers, who planned to hold talks with local
leaders, representatives of political parties and religious
figures in Shkoder, were forced to turn back.
</P>
<P>
Fino convened a special cabinet meeting after returning to
Tirana and strongly condemned this anti-government action,
instructing the Interior and Defense Ministries to start
investigation immediately.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Arben Malaj, who traveled with Fino, said the
gunmen claimed that 120 people from Shkoder were being held in the
southern port of Sarande and demanded their release.
</P>
<P>
Malaj denied the claims but said the government would check
them out.
</P>
<P>
Since Fino took office as the prime minister of the national
reconciliation government on March 12, this is the first time for
him to visit the northern part of the country where he has few
supporters.
</P>
<P>
Although the political crisis in Albania has been relaxing
recently, robbery and terrorism are still rampant in some places.
</P>
<P>
The Albanian government has been calling for an urgent
deployment of an international peace-keeping force in the country.
</P>
<P>
The European Union had agreed to send an Italian-led
6,000-member force to help protect aid delivery to Albania. But
Italy said on Friday it would not be ready until April 14 at the
earliest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
