<DOCNO> XIE19970406.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: ABCs of Basic Law of Hong Kong SAR (5-6) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Following are the ABCs of the
Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (5-6) in
a question-and-answer format:
</P>
<P>
Question: Why should people in the mainland also familiarize
themselves with the Basic Law?
</P>
<P>
Answer: The Basic Law is a law on the Hong Kong SAR, but it is
also a national law to be observed by the whole nation. As a
national law, it safeguards national unity, sovereignty and
territorial integrity, protects national security and the basic
social system of the country, and guarantees direct administration
over the Hong Kong SAR by the central government.
</P>
<P>
By stipulating that the Hong Kong SAR is an inalienable local
administrative region of China, the law helps maintain a
harmonious relationship between Hong Kong and the interior.
</P>
<P>
The Basic Law, therefore, represents the will and interests of
not only Hong Kong compatriots but also the Chinese nation as a
whole. The Basic Law should be abided by not only by the Hong Kong
SAR but also by the central authorities, provinces, autonomous
regions and centrally-administered municipalities, not only by
Hong Kong people but also by people in the interior.
</P>
<P>
To abide by the Basic Law, people must first be familiar with
it.
</P>
<P>
Question: Why will capitalism and the existing way of life in
Hong Kong remain unchanged for 50 years after China resumes the
exercise of sovereignty over it?
</P>
<P>
Answer: On the settlement of the Hong Kong question, Deng
Xiaoping said: "There can be only two ways: one is peaceful, the
other nonpeaceful. To settle the Hong Kong question peacefully, we
have to take into account realities in Hong Kong, and realities in
China and in Britain as well. In other words, the way of settling
the question should be acceptable to all the three sides."
</P>
<P>
"If we were to achieve the reunification (of Hong Kong and the
motherland) with socialism, acceptance by the three sides would be
difficult. A reluctant acceptance would lead to a chaotic
situation. Even if no armed conflict occured, Hong Kong would
become a desolate city with a lot of problems, and that is not a
Hong Kong we hope to have."
</P>
<P>
"So far as the Hong Kong question is concerned, therefore, the
only solution acceptable to all the three sides is the 'one
country, two systems' arrangement, under which Hong Kong is
allowed to retain its capitalist system and maintain its status as
a free port and a financial center. There is no other alternative."
</P>
<P>
Why will Hong Kong be allowed to keep its existing capitalist
system and lifestyle unchanged for 50 years? Deng Xiaoping
said: "This is also based on Chinese realities."
</P>
<P>
"It will take 30-50 years for China to get really developed, or
for it to come close to, rather than surpass, developed
countries. If, before the end of this century, we need to
implement an open policy, then in the first 50 years of the next
century, when China comes closer to developed countries, we need
to continue implementing this policy."
</P>
<P>
"It won't do to discard this policy. Maintaining the prosperity
and stability of Hong Kong accords with China's own vital
interests. When we say '50 years', it is not something spoken of
casually, out of a burst of emotions. It is the result of taking
into account of China's realities and requirements for its
development."
</P>
<P>
"If (China's) open policy remains unchanged in the first 50
years of the next century, then in the second 50 years when we
have more economic exchanges with the rest of the world and when
there is a greater inter-dependence (between China and the rest of
the world), it will be still more impossible for China to change
its open policy."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
