<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Child Care Centers Become Homes For Elderly In Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 6 (Xinhua) -- With a growing population of
elderly and a declining birth rate in Shanghai, China's industrial
and financial center, some child care centers have been
transformed into homes for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai now has 2.27 million people at and above the age of
60, accounting for 17.4 percent of the metropolitan population,
and the city's 330 welfare facilities for old people, which have
15,000 beds, are far from sufficient.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the declining birth rate in recent years has
meant that child care workers are facing the possibility of
unemployment.
</P>
<P>
So, governments at all levels have allocated funds to turn some
of the child care centers into old folks' homes by adding medical
facilities, libraries, and by training people to care for the
elderly.
</P>
<P>
The Putuo District is an experimental area for this, where five
child care centers have been changed into homes for the
elderly. This move has been followed by ten other districts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970406.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wasps Used in Costa Rica to Control Pests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rican agricultural
technicians are using certain types of wasps to eliminate pests
and replace insecticides that have negative impact on human health
and the environment.
</P>
<P>
The "Trichograma" wasp can control some 250 kinds of pests that
threaten cultivation of vegetables and fruits in several parts of
the country, the Agriculture Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
To control one hectare of cultivated land, 120,000 wasps are
needed, at a cost of a little more than two U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Trichograma wasp is used in Russia, South America, the
Caribbean and Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
