<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farmer Makes Wood Carving to Mark Hong Kong's Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, April 6 (Xinhua) -- A farmer in north China's
Hebei province plans to provide the future Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region with a large wood carving, which he made to
mark the return of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The jujube wood carving is 50 cm by 50 cm by 15 cm and is like
the railway connecting Beijing and Kowloon. On its pedestal is an
ox pulling a cart, loaded with the territory of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The carving symbolizes the return of Hong Kong to the
motherland in 1997, the Year of the Ox in the Chinese calendar,
the carver, Wang Ziran, explains.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the rough sculpture, which is made from a
105-kilogram piece of jujube, has high artistic value.
</P>
<P>
Wang spent half a year drawing the design and scouring the
county for the right piece of wood.
</P>
<P>
"To express a farmer's joyous feeling about the return of Hong
Kong and the unification of China, I will give this to Mr. Tung
Chee-hwa, the first chief executive of the future Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region as a gift," said Wang. 
</P>
</TEXT>
