<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Carries Out Seed Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai's new end-of-century
seed project will promote improvement in seed strains used in the
city's rural areas, according to the local agriculture department.
</P>
<P>
The department says that by the year 2000, two generations of
rice strains will be developed and one new generation of wheat and
rapeseed will be worked out. The new seeds will be used in 90
percent of the municipality's farmland.
</P>
<P>
All seeds used in the city will be refined and provided with
proof of brand to avoid falsification in packaging.
</P>
<P>
The plan also calls for fine seed-breeding bases with
technicians and equipment on a large scale.
</P>
<P>
Agricultural experts point out that some factors hindering the
reaching of this goal are diversified research, production and
sales, and poor managment in the seed business.
</P>
<P>
This year, the city will set up three large bases for
municipal-level seed use and inspection, for oil-bearing seeds,
and a rice-breeding base.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai now has nearly 70,000 ha of fine seed-breeding bases
and 75 percent of the seeds used are provided by using
guidelines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
