<HEADLINE> WHO to Mark World Health Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 5 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization
(WHO) said in a press release reaching here today that the World
Health Day will be celebrated throughout the world on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The day will be marked under the theme "Emerging Infectious
Diseases -- Global Alert, Global Response," said WHO
representative in Ethiopia Wedson C. Mwambazi.
</P>
<P>
He said the African continent has been rocked several times by
all sorts of epidemics, which at times were extremely serious.
</P>
<P>
He said the emerging diseases include HIV infestation which
causes AIDS with its subsequent effects of human suffering and
economic burden.
</P>
<P>
The outbreak of the epidemic of Ebola haemorrhagic fever in
1995 in Zaire is among the emerging diseases, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said new or newly detected infectious diseases of glDml
concern include a new form of cholera, bloody diarrhoea, leading
to the haemolytic-uraemic-syndrome, and hepatitis.
